**Performance Tests Notes:**
For a comprehensive setup, I would typically integrate with a tool like JMeter or k6 for external load testing. Within the Java application, performance tests can be done using JUnit combined with `Stopwatch` or by integrating with JMH (Java Microbenchmark Harness) for micro-benchmarking specific code paths.

*   **Example approach for simple performance metrics in integration tests:**
    ```java
    // In an integration test class
    @Test
    @DisplayName("Measure createProject performance")
    void createProject_PerformanceTest() {
        // Prepare test data
        ProjectRequest request = new ProjectRequest();
        request.setName("Performance Project " + System.nanoTime());
        request.setDescription("Performance test project");
        request.setStartDate(LocalDate.now());
        request.setEndDate(LocalDate.now().plusMonths(1));

        long startTime = System.nanoTime();
        // Call the service method multiple times or once for average
        projectService.createProject(request, owner.getId()); // Assuming owner is set up in test
        long endTime = System.nanoTime();
        long duration = (endTime - startTime) / 1_000_000; // milliseconds

        log.info("createProject took {} ms", duration);
        assertTrue(duration < 200, "createProject should be fast enough (under 200ms)"); // Example threshold
    }
    ```
    This can be repeated for critical endpoints or service methods. For full load testing, external tools are recommended.

